Horrible experience! We had planned this trip for a few months and made arrangements to come up from the Los Angeles area. Some of my friends had to take time off of work in order to make this to event.While on route to Santa Barbara, I received a text indicating that Social Cycle cancelled the event because others (not our group) were unable to attend.   They offered no more than a veiled apology for this cancellation. We, on the other hand, spent a combined total of over $750 for a weekend that could have been held elsewhere of our choice. We had no choice but to continue on our plans to go to Santa Barbara for the weekend. We made the best of it but the whole purpose for coming to Santa Barbara was obliterated not by our choice.  Social Cycle is very unapologetic about late cancellations on our part but will do nothing to penalize themselves for any late 11th hour) cancellations on their part.  Regardless of how well you plan your weekend, Social Cycle allows outside influences to affect your plans. Don‚Äôt waste your time. Rent a bike (or multi-person peddling cart) and do it on your own. We did, it was a good time completely under our control.</Review>

<Review>I got a stop sign / limit line traffic ticket, and it was dismissed because of California traffic tickets! It took about six months for the court to finally make a decision so it was a very long process but well worth it.

My ticket was for $238 and knows what my insurance would have increased to if I didn't hire California traffic tickets to help me! Their price to help aide you in this process was about $150-$200 I believe ? I can't remember to be sure. All I know is the cost of their service is still a lot less than it would have been to not take the risk and fight it.

The process to work with California traffic tickets was fairly easy and reasonable and they make it really clear of how to submit your documentation properly. Susie is quick to respond and helpful for any question you have.

The lawyer lays out the written declaration for you and then you submit that with any subsequent proof you want to provide such as pictures of the scene to show you are innocent. Even though the written declaration didn't personally pertain to my exact situation it helped get my ticket dismissed because of the Knowledge of the law and carefully constructed case.

Got a 92mph speeding ticket  going to Vegas last November 2019 from California. It was my first time to get a ticket out of state. Fortunately, I found this law firm on google, and immediately called them the next day. Spoke to Jeff, and was properly given instructions on how I would be able to fight in court. Fast forward to February 2020, I lost my trial which is Trial by Written Declaration. Since they have a two-step strategy, I opted for Trial De Novo to try it again and hope for the best.

Last week, I got an email from them saying they have won my case. All in all, it took 8 months because of the pandemic. In the end, it was all worth it. Got my refund check from the court yesterday.

If you're looking for reputable attorneys, look no further. Trust these people. They are the best chance you'll ever get when it comes to fighting your ticket. Good luck!

(Btw, I'm doing my best not to speed anymore. Learned my lesson)<//review>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
I‚Äôve been taking dogs and cats to Dr. Naqvi at El Cerrito Pet Hospital for years. He and his staff are really terrific and very knowledgeable.

One of my dogs had a food allergy which gave him awful skin problems. Dr. Naqvi showed me how to find exactly what the allergy was by testing Hugo‚Äôs reaction to a single food at a time. He also gave me medicine that knocked out his flare-up really quickly. Within a month, we‚Äôd figured out what his allergy was, so his skin is generally in great shape. I have accidentally given him wheat since then and caused another bad flare up. Dr. Naqvi gave me a spray and a prescription that stopped the flare up in a couple of days, and kept Hugo comfortable while the itchy redness was going away.

He knows his stuff. I have tested this out. One time he told me that my friend‚Äôs dog was coughing primarily due to her just being really fat. I thought there had to be something else going on. So I took her to a different veterinarian, and they examined her, did blood tests, and even took x-rays because I wanted them to be as thorough as possible. Their diagnosis? Her weight was the reason for the terrible cough.

Aside from being really good at treating animals, El Cerrito Pet is even more excellent in the warm heart area. You can see it in how everyone engages with the animals being brought to them for care, and also in how they take care of the humans who bring them in.

My friends is disabled, and can‚Äôt get to the vet without a ride for her and for her wheelchair. I was amazed when I visited her about a year ago and she told me that she didn‚Äôt need me to take her to the vet. Shirley, who runs the front desk, had realized that it was a hassle for her to get there, and had been taking her animals back and forth and also bringing their prescriptions to my friend.

When my friend was in the ICU and desperately ill, each time I would stop by for a free weigh-in for the old, overweight dog (who became normal-sized and spunky by following Dr. Naqvi‚Äôs program of weight loss for her), Dr. Naqvi and all the staff wanted to know how my friend was doing, and asked me to pass on their good wishes for a speedy and full recovery. I know that they prayed for her, too, especially Dr. Naqvi, who is a spiritual man.

I highly recommend El Cerrito Pet Hospital. Dr. Naqvi and his staff are talented and knowledgeable people, and their hearts are wide open for us and for our pets.</Text>

<Review>There's a really nice view here on a sunny day, but the food is a hit or miss.

If you want a hit, stick with the Crab Roll. The roll is super buttery, and the crab was very fresh.
Comforting and delicious.

Tomato bisque was meh. Too watery. The croutons that come with it are better than the soup itself (lots of garlic & parmesan).

I would skip the fish & chips, or more accurately, the fish - it has too much batter and you can barely taste it.
The chips themselves are very actually: they're proper chips, crispy but meaty, potato wedges style, like they should be.<//Review>< pics>

<review>I have not reviewed any place since the pandemic started and to honest it is more difficult to review takeout places since this is new to many establishments and their food is best served in the restaurant. Takeout food  often loses quality during transportation. However, I must give a shout out to Fish. My hub and I are on the search (starting today ) for perfect fish and chips that are crisp, crunching and delicious. Fish did not disappoint. I figured that the drive home would ruin the meal and the crust and fries would be soggy and a mushy mess.  Well woo-hoo Fish have takeout fish and chips down to perfection. Crispy, favorable and if course of the highest quality. And as in the past, the staff are friendly, professional and engaging while still keeping distance.

So friends, it is worth the drive and cost during a time unlike we have experienced before. Happy New Year and stay well and well fed.<//review><pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMBFAnX4XGNLq2uQpq1KPtnuGzisRA2vjgqOnQF=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNCuSGDDdO2zFwpToQJujnf7_MNFWVESowdVzJU=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMldcBoDdLxZlInbp9uAfWj-cROIdavS02wtBqA=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNM2ldBDk740LKH35gy4oXYw01wjjSRoApmAsZe=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMdmKZ0g0gMFkroBzFwPFjNecE2n3OB_rXnSsI_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMa52ycxNqps7Gn-7iIEpivs5ZE3HLZyjg_uufp=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNRdm6f6lWtAUGMUt8C2SBZ7JA5AyJFaC375nju=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOBZ7yszmW5PUwTo-fmOnfSpQWCY9j4IABiQ5_L=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOtINu_J0sJCfs8iSR3aRrXQXSr1oPwGSnI86iD=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipP67pnewrRm9AJqWSW8K_DwQxsvFPnC3XgPpfP0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMm3Wq7qq3iEcIdaZDWO8c81-nrj5vL0twC8cJw=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOpNoX3743_DjMPNm2z_Ho2Ody22n2RUtGQ9f9s=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMkNFoSUKDWxXDXhlaPW8X-XHT0CdlgmZv_YKID=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMbBIBduM1DdVrHp7Xkqzg2LficMwmIw1eKLb1P=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMHE4WNH5hgxImZn3W4AY5yGp-CPMw3mnclrrDy=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPg3VqMWoZqCYeF530gW2bz11Uhh36QwxV0ddFR=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< Response>

< text>
Decent food, but overpriced.  Reviews on other sites say the food is "meh", but I didn't find that to be the case.  But lunch for two people at a seafood place with self service, indoor picnic tables, and restrooms around the corner out back should not come to $68 cash only, not counting tip for the runner who only brings out your food because you need to go back up for your iced tea refills...iced tea, don't go back for lemonade.
Had iced tea, lemonade, fish & chips, a small plate of octopus (2 small bites on 2 skewers), 3 grilled oysters, and 6 raw oysters (that ALL had bits of shell in them).  How does that even happen?
Fish & Chips - Good batter, Octopus - cooked right with flavorful marinade, Grilled Oysters - very good.  Raw oysters - meh, and like I said "why the shell shards?"  I actually have a medical condition that makes it lucky I didn't swallow any.
The food wasn't bad, but I won't be a repeat customer, either.<//text>

<text>ProTip: Order your to-go food ahead by calling the restaurant directly so by the time you arrive, you'll be ready to skip the long (weekend) lines and have your food ready. The outdoor patio in the restaurant proper is nice, but if too crowded, an even better view is from the mini park along the marina at the end of the parking lot.  Grab your to-go food, snag a bench by the water, and enjoy the experience!

If you've already ordered by calling ahead you can skip the line. Just walk right through the gate and look for the to-go pickup area. Pay (card accepted) and go.

<review>The white chowder is one of the best we've had.  It was wonderfully creamy with the broth made with bacon.   The clams were cleaned very well - we didn't taste any grit whatsoever.

Our salmon was beautifully presented with sprinkles of chives and pink Himalayan sea salt.   However it was a bit unevenly cooked and seasoned.

The po' boy sandwich was ok.  It was too soggy for our taste.  We also weren't impressed with the fish and chips.  They were a little dry.</review>< user>

<Name>Hartley K< /Name>< text>
Our favorite spot for a post hike reward. Amazing fish, great atmosphere, tons of outdoor seating. What more could you want? Feels like the only non touristy spot in Sausalito.

Highly recommend: salmon Saigon sando, tuna melt, market fish on greens, tuna poke appetizer, and the fish and chips. Really you can‚Äôt go wrong here.

The line might look long, but it moves quickly. Order at the counter and they bring it out very fast!</text>

<review>‚ÄúThe In-N-Out of FISH‚Äù -heard while waiting in line.

Tip: show up at opening to get a nice spot on the patio on a sunny day! Line starts forming well before opening.

My go-to is the tuna melt now that I‚Äôve been here 3 times, but looking forward to trying some of the other sandwich menu items like the ‚ÄúKorean KFC‚Äù cod sandwich and the cod Reuben. The tuna melt is excellent, by far the freshest tuna I‚Äôve had on a melt. The acme bread is delicious, and portions are huge; ratio of tuna to bread is literally like 3:1! Crab rolls and clams are all excellent as well.

Beautiful views of the bay on the patio, nothing can compete with this combination of food and location!</review><user_name>Eric Miller</user_name><time>1581884762762< /time>< gmap_id>

< Text>
Went here after a hike at Fort Baker and desperately needed some clam chowder to refuel. Had the New England style and was a bit disappointed that it was a bit thin and soupy. Also, it needed to be HOT, not just warm. It was difficult to find the clams, as well. Had fries for a side, and they were good. The garlic bread was absolutely soaking with butter, but at least it was hot and lots of tasty garlic. <user>113731609127846485889< /user>< text>
Really excellent fish and seafood restaurant, one of my favorite places in Sausalito. The restaurant is totally informal, which is part of the charm. You queue up to place your order. They have both indoor seating and outdoor picnic tables with very nice views. The food was delicious - really good quality fish. It does come at a price, but you understand it once it's on your plate! We had a couple of specials on the day - an exquisite rainbow trout main and a mussels starter, both excellent. The chowder is very nice too, as is the fish and chips. Good drinks options are available.<//text>

<user>107326448576429040430< /user><name>Javiera A. Sevilla< /name>< Time>
1502132339926< /Time>
<Rating>3<//Rating><review>Went on a non holiday Sunday, decently sunny but not even a particularly nice day yet the line was out the door past the patio gate. Was with a friend who choose the place so we got in line and (somewhat) patiently waited.  And waited, and waited about 35 minutes just to order.

On top of that, the restrooms are around the back of the building, very small and horrifically maintained. (Was only ~3pm so not near closing)  In addition it is cash only so be prepared or use the ATM they have inside (3dollar fee).

I am all for sustainable, local food but I don't thrill this place was worth the cost, wait and drive out past downtown Sausalito.

They were out of halibut so the fish and chip we ordered used a lower quality fish (price was discounted to $21) they were crisp, 2 larger pieces and two smaller ones with a generous mound of chips (potatoes wedges) the fish was just way too saturated in oil, I tried dabbing a bit with a napkin but honestly it was just soaked through. The chips were less greasy, decently crisp on the outside but a bit mushy potato-y on the inside.
Must say, the tarter sauce was quite good though.

Also ordered the tuna melt, crunch outside of sand which, generous amounts of fish, but far too mushy and sausy, with too many capers- almost lost the sense of actual albacore and tuna.
Came with shoestring fries, a lot of them but rather than shoestring fries they were really the standard thickness.

Decent at first when they were warm but they got cold fast and then became extraordinarily hard, not crispy but just stale/hard.

I like the outdoor seating and general concept yet unfortunately the price was not worth the quality of food, and I felt a tad sick after, definitely needed a nap after only half the tuna melt and 1.5 pieces of the Fish chips due to the heavy amounts of grease.<//review>< pictures>

< Text>
Fish was tasty, but not worth the price. Clam chowder was great.<//Text>
< Time>
1594088660380< /Time>
< rating>
3<//rating>
<user_id>106572723249609819965< /user_id><Pictures>None< /Pictures>< resp>
None<//resp>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< Review>
They were out of the crab roll, so I went with their fish and chips and two specials: the local Dungeness crab and their steamed fish platter.

It is unfortunate that they were out of the crab roll since it looked like the best thing on their list, which is why I docked a star.

The fish and chips are phenomenal. The best I've had.

The Dungeness crab was fantastic as well, but a little pricey for what we got, since it was effectively just the crab plus some dry noodles on top for decoration. If I knew that, I would've bought an  additional entree.

Lastly, their fish platter special effectively was just mussels over potatoes, cabbage, etc. On realization, the platter was named after the restaurant and was misleading since it had zero fish.. in any case, it was really good and I enjoyed it, but it definitely took me for a whirl since I was expecting.. well.. fish.</Review>

< rate>
4</rate>
<user>113059969585892968839< /user>< review>
They take credit cards now!
This place was great. Highly recommend getting there early, we were there 5min after they opened and waited in line maybe 5-8 minutes. When we left around 12:20 there was a line to the parking lot, probably a 25-30min wait.

Raw oysters were great, best I've had in the bay area. Had all three varieties they offered today and they were all delicious.

Crab roll was 10/10, my wife couldn't stop saying how good it was, she said it was the best she's ever had. Tons of meat, no mayo or anything just some butter and hella crab.

I had the Cod fish and chips, pretty standard fare but I was sharing with a 2 year old so had to stay conservative.

Staff was friendly, plenty of seating - outside is mostly community style tables, which I normally dislike but the vibe here makes it work.

Great little view of the harbor.

We will return, this place is a solid Sausalito option.</review>

Great place.   Prices seemed reasonable for the area. Unique walk-up/cash-only place. Halibut fish & chips were great as well as the Peacemaker fried oyster sandwich. Tom Cooke< /Name>
<date>1468852871782</date><Rating>3< /Rating>< review>
Reasonably Tasty, Highly Priced

I would echo a lot of the other reviews that I‚Äôve read (after eating here)‚Äîit‚Äôs good food, but it seems a little pricey.

I have no doubt that everything we ate was incredibly fresh, but over $70 for 3 lunches (and one beer) is a little rich for my wallet.  And the no cash rule seems a little anachronistic nowadays.

That being said, the sandwiches were large and very tasty.  However, I was disappointed with my Fish Tacos.  There were vary generous portions of grilled fish, however, they were so generous that they overwhelmed the small tortillas.  So, it was basically inedible as a taco‚Äîwhat I consider a ‚Äòhand meal‚Äô‚Äîand had to be eaten with a knife and fork.  For me, this spoils the flavor experience‚ÄîI ended up with a bunch of food all over my plate, without the nice balance of fish, cabbage, tortilla, sauce that I‚Äôd expect from a taco.  It seemed I ended up with a bite of each thing, one at a time.  So, larger tortillas, please!

Food was quickly prepared and delivered (you order at the counter, get a number, find a table).  There was a constant line of people, often 15-20 deep, but it seemed to flow pretty quickly.

It‚Äôs a great location, and a wonderful deck to sit and look at the boats and the bay, but to be honest, I‚Äôll explore other spots before I come back.<//review>

The view and atmosphere of the restaurant are great. Paying only in cash is not, especially given the high prices on their food. I had the $17 tuna melt. I was expecting to be wowed by a tuna sandwich that expensive. Unfortunately, it was mushy and absolutely packed full of capers. I couldn't even taste the tuna. <username>Morgan Lai</username><date>1519548483400</date><Rating>5< /Rating>< Review>
Food way exceeded my expectations. Pricey, but the portions are huge, maybe big enough to share for two.

Pasta Con Vongole ($22): Homemade pasta. Clams overflowing. A very flavorful white wine sauce. Chile flakes for an added kick. Bliss.

Squid daily special: Shame this one isn't always available because it's fantastic. Had the option for getting it over salad or pasta and went with the pasta. Spicy and garlic aplenty for the sauce, but without the white wine from the pasta. Still great. The squid had an incredible wood BBQ'd flavor I've never experienced in squid before, I loved it.

White Chowder Bowl ($9 bowl): An all-around solid, classic bowl of New England chowder.

Pay the counter before you order, cash only.<//Review>

<user>108974765489459336063< /user><name>Michelle Rowe<//name><date>1393616190197< /date>< rating>
4</rating>
<Text>This spot is really amazing!
I came here on my bike after walking around Sausalito. It was recommended by my friend I was with and it did meet my expectations. We ordered the crab roll and it was delicious! So buttery! We got coleslaw with it, and I'm usually not a fan of coleslaw but I liked this one. It was a vinaigrette coleslaw instead of a mayonnaise based slaw. The bread they use for the roll was the perfect balance of crisp outer crust to soft center.
The inside is very laid back with benches to sit at and has a great coastal feel to it. There is plenty of outside seating too with heaters if it's a little on the chilly side.
I would have rated this place higher but they don't have a place to lock up your bike and it is cash only, so make sure you pull out at least $60 for dinner or lunch for two!<//Text>< Pics>

< Review>
Food is great. Their fish, crab, oysters, and hot plate specials like paella are all great. Things may be a little but on the plain side, but mostly great. However, employees at the register are sometimes rude during busy hours and accepts cash only. Also, it seems like prices have risen, although quantity seems to have become bigger too. Soups are served lukewarm during late afternoon rush times in the weekends.
(Dozen oysters, a soda, crab roll, chowder, and pasta came out to be almost 100 dollars)<//Review>

Ashi Vinod<//user_name>
<Date>1527453999660</Date>< rating>
3< /rating>
< text>
You can't go wrong with the view at the FISH restaurant.

We reached here at 11am and they don't begin serving the customers until 11.30am. The lines are out the door. I'm not kidding. This place was rated for best seafood on Michelin and yelp.

Based on the two reviews, people mentioned they only accept cash. Good news!! They have started to accept credit cards and they have ATM machine inside the restaurant too. They have plenty of sitting inside and outside.

And it's a kid friendly restaurant.

Food: we ordered fish and chips( Fish was fresh and cooked perfectly). It lacked flavors. The baked oysters were great but I left they were tiny. The Portuguese clam chowder was a little Salty. That was my least favorite.

Overall food is a little pricey. Fish and chips were  $21. 3 oysters for $9.

I don't mind coming back to try the rest of the menu.<//text>

< Text>
I ordered the Crab sandwich after seeing this on the Food Network.  Along with the sandwich I had a side of the house made slaw.  The slaw was quite tasty and did not have the mayonnaise sauce that most of us have come to expect of the plethora of food service establishments.
The Crab sandwich was an overall great experience that exemplified the taste of the crab.  Cooked in just a bit of butter with a touch of herb(s) and then layered onto homemade bread, this was a fantastic combination.
I thought the price was a bit high, but then again, I am also from the Mid-west where things are a bit cheaper.< /Text>

<username>Jason S<//username><date>1473036589587< /date>< rate>
5<//rate>
< review>
Fish.  Another instant favorite happened upon during a recent visit to the Bay Area.  It was a last-minute gamble discovered through Google Maps while standing at Battery Spencer early on a Friday evening.  I visited with a group of friends and we were all pleasantly surprised how perfectly this met our needs.  Apart from Fish, the marina area was essentially deserted - no cars, no people, it was wonderfully quiet and relaxed, right there on the waterfront.  I don't know if that is normal, but it was awesome.  Tons of available free parking - so simple.  What a great way to chill out after a big day.  The patio offers large, picnic table seating, so we had no problem gathering as a group of six for a laid-back, outdoor dinner.  I opted for the fish and chips with lemonade.  Yes. This was a good choice!  Plus, all of the (huge) salads and other items I saw people enjoying at other tables looked equally inviting.  As a huge bonus (for me), the speakers were calmly piping out lazy guitar blues - the mellow, Mississippi kind of stuff and other varieties (think Fred McDowell, John Hurt, Stefan Grossman and similar).  I *loved* this place!!  I will make an out-of-the-way effort to stop here again on any future trip into the area.  Not to be missed.</review>

< review>
The food is 5-star, the ambiance is 4-star and because it's cash-only it's a 2-star for convenience in my book. 110299416919250566661< /user_id>
<name>Mark Jarrard Jr< /name><Date>1316757528057</Date>< Rating>
4<//Rating>
< Text>
I ordered the Crab sandwich after seeing this on the Food Network.  Along with the sandwich I had a side of the house made slaw.  The slaw was quite tasty and did not have the mayonnaise sauce that most of us have come to expect of the plethora of food service establishments.
The Crab sandwich was an overall great experience that exemplified the taste of the crab.  Cooked in just a bit of butter with a touch of herb(s) and then layered onto homemade bread, this was a fantastic combination.
I thought the price was a bit high, but then again, I am also from the Mid-west where things are a bit cheaper.<//Text>

<text>A great place to go,
if you love standing in lines,
if not, save your time.

I usually don't write reviews until after I've eaten. However, I've been in line over an hour and have decided the quality of food can't possibly bring the rating beyond 3 stars. Inefficiency bugs me, and this place is a marvel of inefficiency. Giant line, cash only, and all seemingly intentional to give a show of being an old school dining experience. Hipsters without soul.

Pro tip: it took so long to get to the front that we ended up ordering take out. In spite of the fact that was asked the lady behind the bar about take out and she didn't tell us we can order there, it appears you actually can. So my recommendation would be to skip the line and order take out at the bar.</text>< date>

Delicious sustainable seafood from chowder to grilled fish with pasta. Try oysters and shoestring fries. Local beer and wines.< /review>
</record></dataset><record>
< Review>
To preface this review I hate crowds. Go early! I have been coming here since I was a kid and only locals new about this spot. It was childhood favorite over looking Sausalito Bay, now it is just overcrowded. There are more food options and they serve beer which is nice. It use to be more of a fish monger spot but now it is more of a tourist restaurant.

The food is good and I am glad that the fish is caught sustainably. I am just sad that it is so crowded. #gentrification< /Review>

Daipeng<//name>
<Date>1452456246049<//Date><Rating>2< /Rating>< text>
Very generous with potatoes.  If you get fries with their scallop roll, you will get plenty of potatoes. Clam chowder is half potatoes and not very creamy. Fish tacos come with very little fish,  a ton of cilantro, 3 palm size tortillas. Dishes are not very filling for the price you pay.  At least it's sustainable. Also it's cash only but they have an atm. They play old but good songs and the atmosphere along with the ketchup is pretty good.<//text>

<Rate>3<//Rate><Text>Love the idea of sustainable seafood, but I was underwhelmed after my meal.  We had the white chowder, black cod (one of the fishes of the day), and the Saigon sandwich.  The chowder was good, but the sandwich was overly salty which was disappointing for costing $24 and the portion for the fish of the day was small.  The prices are a bit high to be cash only.  We arrived just before noon and there was about a 10-15 minute wait to place our order.  When we left just before 1pm, the line was 4 times as long.  So get there early if you can.</Text>< userid>

101684759371052236980</user>
< review>
Wow this place is awesome. Casual restaurant, where you line up to order. Price is high, but worth it since the quality of the seafood is great.

We got the following
- Clam Chowder - ok, not a heavy clam chowder.
- Crab Roll - Amazing. lots of tender crab with a soft roll. This dish can be shared since it comes with a ton of shoestring fries.
- Ceviche - very good, has fresh fish and plenty of chips.

Seating outside is nice if the weather is good. You will have to get your own silverware etc, but its not a big deal. Price is high due to sustainable seafood, but in my opinion it's worth it.< /review>

<pictures>None<//pictures><Text>There was a long line and the people in line in front of us were first timers as well so ..we didn't have a recommendation on what to order.

Not the best place I've ever had salmon but, the locals think this place is the bomb. I thought the trout was better than the salmon. The salmon over noodles was unnecessarily spicy with red Chile peppers (why a pizza condiment? I don't know) and the noodles were undercooked. The white clam chowder was bland, kinda like cream of potato soup.

< text>
3.5 rounded to 4 stars. Long, long wait. But service is quick once you actually order. Clam dip was ok, chips served with it were not good but I had also ordered garlic bread and that was so much better with it. Garlic bread was delicious and dripping with butter.  Also tried both clam chowders. I have never had a red chowder before so I can't compare but it was pretty tasty but I barely had any clam in it! White chowder was just ok and was also low on clams.

Tried special salmon frame bits. I wasn't thrilled with that either but my friend really enjoyed it. Also tried my friend's albacore tuna from the tacos. Fish was so fresh!

Overall experience was just ok. Some hits and some misses. Also pretty pricey< /text>

<Rating>5<//Rating><Review>Great view, ambience and awesome fish and chips!< /Review><Pictures>None</Pictures><response>None<//response><gmapID>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>
< user>
104589054600774963024<//user>
<Name>Andrew McMann< /Name>< time>
1341591173921< /time>
< rate>
3< /rate>
< review>
Typically Californian eco-aware cafe with but with a crusty old eastern seaboard dive ambiance interior. Most diners sit outside, at picnic tables on the large harbor side deck to take in the views, and salt air. The place is popular - there is often a long line of hungry folks (15 deep) willing to wait for the fresh, local fish served on any given day. (Open 7 days). The grilled catch of the day (wild salmon, farm raised  trout, black cod when we were there recently) grilled to order and served on a large mixed green salad or sandwich style. The ceviche was very good - with plenty of good sized chunks of white fish, lime juice, red onions, grapefruit, cilantro and avocado. The crab parfait was interesting - but the sweet pepper jelly layer made the whole concoction a tad too sweet. Fish and chips - we could really taste the beer in the beer batter. Fish tacos were very disappointing to the wife. Dry fish, disintegrating mini tortillas, mediocre salsa, no avocado.<//review>

< UserId.>
113905467779025537818< /UserId.>
<user_name>Steven Hines< /user_name><Time>1448382154835</Time><Rating>2<//Rating>< review>
It's very expensive, and the waits are very long. The views are fantastic and the food is good. They take only cash (there's an ATM on site). There seafood is locally sourced (the names of the boats that caught the fish are on the daily menu). We don't eat here any more, sadly, since they took the opportunity to put fois gras on the menu; it has nothing to do with their food, they did it just because they could.< /review>
< pics>
None< /pics>
<Resp>None</Resp>< GmapID>
0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13< /GmapID>
</record></dataset><record>
<UserId.>105603284385958429156</UserId.>< review>
If I could put 3.5 stars I would. The food was okay. Not as amazing as I expected from all the previous reviews.

Our first dish was the clam chowder, which was my favorite dish. They had another soup option that was tomato based, we also got that one but the taste had too much spices for my liking.

Second dish we got was a special of the day - baked clams. The clams were huge! Super chewy and fresh, but I think they tried to do too much with the taste. There was the basic lemon and salt and butter. But they added some seaweed and something else I couldn't quite figure out and that made the taste too complicated. This restaurant gets such fresh seafood that they should have just kept it simple and play out the freshness of the clams instead.

Last dish we got was the halibut fish n chips. The fish were perfectly fried. The batter tasted a bit sweet that it reminded me of donuts.

All in all, a great experience and a decent restaurant in Sausalito. The service was impeccable, the cashier who takes your order was very patient with everyone. Most people asked her about various items on the menu and what were her recs and she would repeat nicely what she's been saying to a lot of the people in line. Also the ambiance of the restaurant makes all the food taste a bit better especially if you sit on the patio. It's right next to the water and with nice weather, it'll make your experience that much better.< /review>

<review>Cash only, ATM on site.

Thin clam chowder, not your usual thick and creamy ones. There were bits of bacon, thin slices of clam and a lot of potatoes. Taste itself seemed lacking...didn't have that seafood flavor. Wouldn't order again.

At $3 per oyster on the half shell, you'd expect them to have decent preparation. The oysters themselves tasted fresh, but it was the chunks of shell buried within the oysters that was the most off putting. Having to spit several times between each bite was not classy.< /review><pics>None<//pics><Resp>None< /Resp><gmapID>0x8085850475ffcf03:0x9a43256e5e3b4c13< /gmapID></record>

<userid>111719635748795444946</userid><user_name>John B<//user_name>< Time>
1364314217075</Time>
<rating>4</rating>< Review>
Was met by a huge line at 3:00 on a weekend, and almost left because of it. But the line goes fairly quickly, and once ordered, the food comes out very quickly. Sure you are paying a decent amount for fish and chips, but they are good, and you are eating them outside with beautiful views. We got a cup of ceviche, a bowl of guacamole and an order of fish and chips to share... more than enough for two people; we were stuffed. Some of the best ceviche and most generous portion I've had, would highly recommend. An Anchor Steam lager or a fresh Arnold Palmer goes nicely too.
Take a walk afterward and check out the houseboats: very cool.</Review>

<Rating>1</Rating><text>I was disappointed all around by this restaurant. The location is excellent, there's good music playing, and the staff are reasonably friendly. This is where we go downhill: the food is not great. In the order that I consumed them: Clam Chowder. Ordered in a bowl, this clam chowder was WATERY. While it had chunks of potato and bacon, I did not see any clam whatsoever. It came from a large warmer just behind the counter. The cut of sourdough bread that accompanied it was burnt.The Shandy (Beer/Lemonade) was flat, first and foremost. This might have been saved by being mixed with a good lemonade, but the lemonade conveyed neither sweet nor tart taste. I could not finish it. The Rockfish sandwich was cooked thoroughly, and still agreeably juicy throughout, but had no flavor whatsoever and clearly had not been seasoned. The greens that came with it looked fresh, and tasted good, but we're not enough to save the bland filet. The tartar sauce is unimpressive as well. Awfully expensive for being so unimpressive at that.  I hope someone sees this and makes a change.</text>< pics>

<username>Sandy Tang< /username><time>1441251228916< /time>< rating>
4< /rating>
< Text>
CEVICHE ($14)
Generous portions of fish! I love it when the ceviche has more fish than "fillers" (aka onions). There were at least 3 types of fish and a perfect amount of chips to go with it. If I ever come back, I'll get the ceviche again.

FISH + CHIPS ($24 - omg)
I didn't eat this one but the price of this shocked me. There's three decently large pieces of fried fish with plain fries but I don't think I've ever paid over $15 for good fish and chips. Price definitely scared me away here.

We waited about 30 minutes in line to order at the cashier. The food came to the table pretty quickly though, so that's a winner.

Overall, pretty good place. Just a bit pricey.

CASH & CHECK (I know, how often does that happen?) ONLY.< /Text>
